mux_in[1] = 0`\n   - `mux_in[3] = c ? d : 0` (Uses 1 2-to-1 MUX)\n   - `mux_in[0] = c ? 1 : d` (Uses 1 2-to-1 MUX)\n   - `mux_in[2] = c ? (d_not) : d`? Still need `~d`. \n   \n   Let's look at the K-map for $mux_{in}[2]$ again. Is it possible I misread the columns? \n   $ab$ is the header. $cd$ is the side. \n   $cd=00, ab=10 \rightarrow 1$\n   $cd=01, ab=10 \rightarrow 0$\n   $cd=11, ab=10 \rightarrow 0$\n   $cd=10, ab=10 \rightarrow 1$\n   Yes, it is XNOR. \n   \n   Is there any other way to implement $mux_{in}[2]$? \n   Maybe the 2-to-1 MUXes can use the outputs of other MUXes? \n   Wait, the requirement is to implement the K-map. The K-map is a function of $a, b, c, d$. The 4-to-1 MUX is the *top* level. The TopModule provides the inputs to this MUX. \n   If I use $mux_{in}[2] = c ? (d \text{ XNOR } 1) : d$? No. \n   Let's assume standard MUX logic where constants 0 and 1 are allowed. \n   $mux_{in}[0] = c \text{ OR } d = c ? 1 : d$\n   $mux_{in}[1] = 0\n   $mux_{in}[2] = c \text{ XNOR } d = c ? (d ? 0 : 1) : (d ? 0 : 1)$? No, that's not right. \n   $c \text{ XNOR } d$: if $c=0, \text{out}=d$; if $c=1, \text{out}=\text{NOT } d$.\n   To get $NOT\text{ }d$ using a 2-to-1 MUX: $d \text{ XNOR } 1 = d ? 0 : 1$. \n   So $mux_{in}[2] = c ? (d ? 0 : 1) : (d ? 0 : 1)$ is just constant? No. \n   $mux_{in}[2] = c ? (d ? 0 : 1) : (d ? 0 : 1)$ is wrong. \n   $c \text{ XNOR } d$: \n   - if $c=0$, $out = \text{NOT } d$ (Wait, if $c=0, d=0 \rightarrow 1$; $c=0, d=1 \rightarrow 0$. So $out = \text{NOT } d$)\n   - if $c=1$, $out = d$ (Wait, if $c=1, d=0 \rightarrow 1$; $c=1, d=1 \rightarrow 0$. So $out = \text{NOT } d$)\n   Let's re-re-check the K-map values for $ab=10$ (column 4):\n   $cd=00 \rightarrow 1$\n   $cd=01 \rightarrow 0$\n   $cd=11 \rightarrow 0$\n   $cd=10 \rightarrow 1$\n   Wait, $cd=10$ is $c=1, d=0$. $cd=00$ is $c=0, d=0$. \n   So if $d=0$, $out=1$. If $d=1$, $out=0$. \n   This means $mux_{in}[2] = \text{NOT } d$. It doesn't even depend on $c$! \n   Let's re-verify the whole column $ab=10$: \n   $cd=00: 1$\n   $cd=01: 0$\n   $cd=11: 0$ (Wait, $cd=11$ is $c=1, d=1$. K-map says 1? No, let's look: $cd=11, ab=10$ is 1 in my previous note, but let me look at the text again.)\n   \n   Text K-map:\n   cd\\ab | 00 | 01 | 11 | 10\n   00 | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1\n   01 | 1 | 0 | 0 | 0\n   11 | 1 | 0 | 1 | 1\n   10 | 1 | 0 | 0 | 1\n\n   Column $ab=10$ ($mux_{in}[2]$):\n   $cd=00 \rightarrow 1$\n   $cd=01 \rightarrow 0$\n   $cd=11 \rightarrow 1$\n   $cd=10 \rightarrow 1$\n   Let's re-read the column $ab=10$ carefully: $1, 0, 1, 1$. \n   $cd=00: 1$, $cd=01: 0$, $cd=11: 1$, $cd=10: 1$. \n   This is $(c \text{ OR } \text{NOT } d)$. \n   Let's check: \n   $c=0, d=0 \rightarrow 0|1 = 1$ (Correct)\n   $c=0, d=1 \rightarrow 0|0 = 0$ (Correct)\n   $c=1, d=1 \rightarrow 1|0 = 1$ (Correct)\n   $c=1, d=0 \rightarrow 1|1 = 1$ (Correct)\n   \n   Okay, let's re-evaluate all columns with this strict reading:\n   $ab=00$ ($mux_{in}[0]$): $0, 1, 1, 1 \rightarrow (c \text{ OR } d)$\n   $ab=01$ ($mux_{in}[1]$): $0, 0, 0, 0 \rightarrow 0$\n   $ab=11$ ($mux_{in}[3]$): $0, 0, 1, 1 \rightarrow (c \text{ AND } d)$\n   $ab=10$ ($mux_{in}[2]$): $1, 0, 1, 1 \rightarrow (c \text{ OR } \text{NOT } d)$\n\n   Now, can we implement these using 2-to-1 MUXes (with constants 0, 1 allowed)? \n   - $mux_{in}[0] = c ? 1 : d$\n   - $mux_{in}[1] = 0$\n   - $mux_{in}[3] = c ? d : 0$\n   - $mux_{in}[2] = c ? 1 : (d ? 0 : 1)$ (Wait, $c=0 \rightarrow \text{NOT } d$. $c=1 \rightarrow 1$. So $c ? 1 : \text{NOT } d$.)\n   \n   Wait, how to get $\text{NOT } d$ using a 2-to-1 MUX? If we assume we can use the constant 1 and 0, then $\text{NOT } d = d ? 0 : 1$. \n   So $mux_{in}[2] = c ? 1 : (d ? 0 : 1)$. \n\n   Total 2-to-1 MUXes used: \n   1. $mux_{in}[0]$ uses 1 MUX.\n   2. $mux_{in}[3]$ uses 1 MUX.\n   3. $mux_{in}[2]$ uses 2 MUXes (one for NOT $d$, one for the $c$ selection).\n   Total = 4. \n\n   Wait, is there a more efficient way for $mux_{in}[2]$? \n   $c \text{ OR } \text{NOT } d$ is actually $\text{NOT } (c \text{ AND } d)$? No. \n   $c \text{ OR } \text{NOT } d$ is $\text{NOT } (\text{NOT } c \text{ AND } d)$. \n   Let's use the $c ? 1 : (d ? 0 : 1)$ approach. \n\n   Final check on the K-map column $ab=10$ again. \n   $cd=00 \rightarrow 1$\n   $cd=01 \rightarrow 0$\n   $cd=11 \rightarrow 1$\n   $cd=10 \rightarrow 1$\n   Yes. \n\n   Final check on $ab=11$: $0, 0, 1, 1 \rightarrow (c \text{ AND } d)$. \n   $cd=00: 0, cd=01: 0, cd=11: 1, cd=10: 1$. \n   Yes, $c \text{ AND } d$. \n\n   Final check on $ab=00$: $0, 1, 1, 1 \rightarrow (c \text{ OR } d)$. \n   $cd=00: 0, cd=01: 1, cd=11: 1, cd=10: 1$. \n   Yes, $c \text{ OR } d$. \n\n   Final check on $ab=01$: $0, 0, 0, 0 \rightarrow 0$. \n   Yes.\n\n   Wait, the prompt says $mux_{in}$ is 4 bits. The 4-to-1 MUX takes $mux_{in}$ as input and uses $a, b$ as selectors. The 4-to-1 MUX is *not* part of the TopModule. The TopModule is the part that *provides* the 4 inputs to that MUX. \n   So $mux_{in}[0]$ is the input for $ab=00$. \n   $mux_{in}[1]$ is the input for $ab=01$. \n   $mux_{in}[2]$ is the input for $ab=10$. \n   $mux_{in}[3]$ is the input for $ab=11$. \n   (Note: the prompt says $ab=00$ is $mux_{in}[0]$, $ab=01$ is $mux_{in}[1]$, $ab=11$ is $mux_{in}[3]$, so $ab=10$ must be $mux_{in}[2]$).\n\n   Wait, the prompt says: \"The mux takes as input {a,b} and ab = 00 is connected to mux_in[0], ab=01 is connected to mux_in[1], and so on.\" \n   This means:\n   $mux_{in}[0]$ corresponds to $ab=00$\n   $mux_{in}[1]$ corresponds to $ab=01$\n   $mux_{in}[2]$ corresponds to $ab=10$\n   $mux_{in}[3]$ corresponds to $ab=11$\n\n   Let's re-map the K-map columns to these indices:\n   $mux_{in}[0] (ab=00) = c | d$\n   $mux_{in}[1] (ab=01) = 0$\n   $mux_{in}[2] (ab=10) = c | ~d$\n   $mux_{in}[3] (ab=11) = c & d$\n\n   Wait, the K-map shows $ab$ as the column header. Usually, the first column is 00, then 01, then 11, then 10. \n   Let's check the header: `00 01 11 10`. \n   Yes, that matches my mapping. \n\n   Final Logic:\n   `mux_in[0] = c | d` \n   `mux_in[1] = 0` \n   `mux_in[2] = c | ~d` \n   `mux_in[3] = c & d` \n\n   Implementation using 2-to-1 MUXes (syntax: `sel ? in1 : in0`):\n   `mux_in[0] = c ? 1'b1 : d` \n   `mux_in[1] = 1'b0` \n   `mux_in[2] = c ? 1'b1 : (d ? 1'b0 : 1'b1)` \n   `mux_in[3] = c ? d : 1'b0` \n\n   Wait, is there a way to do `mux_in[2]` with only one 2-to-1 MUX? \n   If $c=1$, $out=1$. If $c=0$, $out=\\text{NOT } d$. \n   Can we use $c$ or $d$ or $0$ or $1$ to get $c | ~d$ in one MUX? \n   $mux = sel ? in1 : in0$. \n   If $sel=c$, $mux = c ? 1 : \text{NOT } d$. Still need $\text{NOT } d$.\n   Wait, $c | ~d$ is the same as $\text{NOT } (\text{NOT } c \text{ AND } d)$. \n   Is there any other way? $c | ~d$ is also $c \text{ OR } \text{XNOR}(d, 0)$? No. \n   Actually, $c | ~d$ is the same as $c$ or $d$ being $0,1$ or $1,0$ or $1,1$. \n   The only case it is $0$ is $c=0, d=1$. \n   So $mux_{in}[2] = \text{NOT } (c == 0 \text{ AND } d == 1)$? No.\n   Let's stick to the 2-to-1 MUX implementation. \n   To avoid syntax errors: ensure all signals are `logic`, use `always @(*)` for combinational logic, and match the port names exactly. \n\n   One detail: The prompt says `mux_in` is 4 bits. The testbench uses `mux_in_dut`. \n   The interface is `output logic [3:0] mux_in`. \n\n   Let's double check the K-map for $ab=10$ one more time. It is the last column.\n   $cd=00: 1$\n   $cd=01: 0$\n   $cd=11: 1$\n   $cd=10: 1$\n   Yes. This is $c | ~d$.\n   \n   Wait, the K-map order of inputs is $a, b, c, d$. The problem says $a, b$ are selectors. $c, d$ are the other inputs. \n   The mapping is correct. \n",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic c,\n    input  logic d,\n    output logic [3:0] mux_in\n);\n\n    // Combinational logic for the 4 inputs of the 4-to-1 MUX\n    // mux_in[0] is for ab=00: c | d\n    // mux_in[1] is for ab=01: 0\n    // mux_in[2] is for ab=10: c | ~d\n    // mux_in[3] is for ab=11: c & d\n\n    always @(*) begin\n        // mux_in[0] = c | d implemented via 2-to-1 MUX: c ? 1 : d\n        mux_in[0] = c ? 1'b1 : d;\n\n        // mux_in[1] = 0\n        mux_in[1] = 1'b0;\n\n        // mux_in[2] = c | ~d implemented via 2-to-1 MUXes: c ? 1 : (~d)\n        // Since ~d is not a MUX, we use a 2-to-1 MUX to implement NOT d: d ? 0 : 1\n        mux_in[2] = c ? 1'b1 : (d ? 1'b0 : 1'b1);\n\n        // mux_in[3] = c & d implemented via 2-to-1 MUX: c ? d : 0\n        mux_in[3] = c ? d : 1'b0;\n    end\n\nendmodule"
